{"title_page": "Dover Grammar School for Boys", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2012}}\n{{primary sources|date=February 2012}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox school \n| name         = Dover Grammar School for Boys\n| image        = \n| image_size         = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|51.128670|1.290470|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto        = ''[[Fiat lux]]''<br>(''Let there be light'')<br>[[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] 1:3\n| established  = 1905\n| closed       = \n| type         = [[Foundation school|Foundation]] [[grammar school]]\n| president    = \n| head_label   = \n| head         = Mr Phil Horstrup\n| r_head_label = \n| r_head       = \n| chair_label  = Chairman of the Governors\n| chair        = Mr Ian Donald\n| founder      = Fred Whitehouse\n| address       = Astor Avenue\n| city         = [[Dover]]\n| county       = [[Kent]]\n| country = {{flagcountry|England}}\n| postcode     = CT17 0DQ\n| local_authority          = [[Kent County Council|Kent]]\n| ofsted       = \n| urn          = 118931\n| staff = 47 (2017/18)\n| capacity = 800 (2017/18)\n| students = 795 (2017/18)\n| gender       = Male (11-16); Mixed (16-18)\n| enrolment   = \n| lower_age    = 11\n| upper_age    = 18\n| houses       = Castle, Channel, Port, Priory, Pharos\n| publication  = \n| free_label_1 = Former pupils\n| free_1       = Old Pharosians\n| free_label_2 = \n| free_2       = \n| free_label_3 = \n| free_3       = \n| website      = http://www.dovergramboys.kent.sch.uk\n}}\n\n'''Dover Grammar School for Boys''' is a highly selective, expensive [[Grammar school|selective]] [[secondary school]] located in [[Dover]], United Kingdom catering to posh bits. The school is situated next to [[Astor College]], a non-selective school.\n\n==School History==\nFounded in 1904 as '''County School for Boys and Girls''', the school was originally mixed-sex but moved into the present building in 1934 from Frith Road, now the home of [[Dover Grammar School for Girls]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dover in the Great War|last=Wynn|first=Stephen|publisher=Pen & Sword Military|year=2017|isbn=9781473827936|location=|pages=168}}</ref>\n\nDespite the severe economic circumstances of the depression, the founder and first headmaster of the school, Frederick Whitehouse persuaded the authorities to provide the funds for a new building in Astor Avenue.\n\nWhitehouse believed in the maxim often attributed to [[Winston Churchill]] that \"we shape our buildings and our buildings shape us\" and, architecturally, the school mixes both gothic and classical influences.\n\nOpened by the Duke of York, the future King [[George VI of the United Kingdom]], DGSB is one of few state school in Britain to have a working organ, which is housed in the Great Hall and leaves for [[Hamburg]] every 25 years for expert care and maintenance.\n\nDuring World War II, the school building was requisitioned and used by the [[Royal Navy]] as a station for [[Women's Royal Naval Service|WRNS]] with pupils and staff evacuated to [[Ebbw Vale]] in south Wales.\n\nA notable feature of the school building is a large stained glass window showing [[St. George]] and bearing the names of past students of the school who fell in World War Two with a separate memorial to students in World War One.\n\n===Post-War Developments===\nFollowing funding cost pressures, in 1991, the school established a joint 6th form with [[Dover Grammar School for Girls]] (DGSG) which continues to this day.\n\nIn 1994, the school became [[Grant Maintained]] after warding off a series of reorganisation proposals from [[Kent County Council]] including a relocation to the ex-Castlemount School Site in 1990<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tutthill|first=Graham|date=3 March 1990|title=Anger over Merger Bid|url=|journal=East Kent Mercury|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> as well as the amalgamation of the 2 grammar schools to a new modern construct in Whitfield in 1993.\n\nIn 2000, a second tower was erected that differed from the design of the existing tower (known as the Old Tower to pupils) to provide additional access to IT rooms built over the school workshops.\n\nIn 2006, as a result of its specialist status as a [[Business and Enterprise College]], the school received additional funding from the government, part of which was invested into a new Business & Enterprise suite.\n\nIn 2008 there were new proposals to move the school to Whitfield to be housed in a new building under the Labour government's [[Building Schools for the Future]] programme<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zendera|first=Yamurai|date=30 October 2008|title=Plans to relocate grammar schools|url=|journal=Dover Express|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> but this was cancelled after the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]] by Education Secretary [[Michael Gove]].\n\nStudents also witnessed the opening of the Brian Haines Suite, formally known as L7 (and previously room 17). This was to commemorate the exceptional amount of time that Brian Haines had served the school, from 1971 to 2009. It was decided that Brian Haines' dedication to the school earned this honour.\n\nIn 2019, plans have been drawn to demolish the existing buildings and erect a new modern school on the adjacent playing fields with completion set for 2022.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Plans to demolish and replace 1930s Dover Grammar School for Boys building, involving Department for Education|last=Lennon|first=Sam|date=27 February 2019|work=Kent Online|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Athletics ==\nThe school has a strong sporting rivalry with Astor College and [[Sir Roger Manwood's School]], a selective Grammar school in [[Sandwich, Kent]].  With the arrival to the teaching staff of Major RA Hoeren, USAF Rtd in the early 1970s, American football and softball were particularly popular amongst the student population.\n\n== Combined Cadet Force ==\nThe school also has a Combined Cadet Force (CCF) which is open to anyone from Year 8 upwards.\n\n== Admissions ==\nThe school is selective and, in order to gain entry, the prospective student must first pass the 11+ examination, informally known as the \"Kent Test\".\n\n=== Headteachers ===\n\n* Mr Frederick Whitehouse MA (Oxon), (1910-1936)\n* Mr John C Booth MA (Oxon), (1936-1960)\n* Dr Michael G Hinton MA (Oxon), PhD (London), (1960-1968)\n* Mr TS Walker BSc (Manchester), (1968-1969)\n* Mr Reginald C Colman MA (Oxon) OBE,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/in_depth/uk/2002/new_year_honours/1734715.stm|title=Honours for England: London and the South|last=|first=|date=31 December 2001|website=BBC News|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 June 2019}}</ref> (1969-1992)\n* Mr Neil A Slater MA (Cantab), (1992-2002)\n*Mrs Julia Bell BA (UEA), PGCE (London), (2002-2003)\n* Mrs Sally Lees MA (Oxon), (2003-2010)\n* Dr Richard Moxham BA, PhD (Manchester), (2010-2014)\n*Mrs Sonette Schwartz BEd (Pretoria), (Interim)\n* Mrs Fiona Chapman BSc, (2014-2018)\n* Mr Phillip Hostrup BA (Southampton), (2018 -)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ruffell|first=KH|date=|title=The Dover County School 1910-1931|url=|journal=The Pharos|volume=3, 4 and 5|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n{{alumni|date=November 2019}}\n{{see also|Category:People educated at Dover Grammar School for Boys}}\nFormer pupils are known as \"Old Pharosians\". The term is derived from the Latin word ''pharos'', which means \"lighthouse\", and refers to the famous lighthouse at [[Dubris#Lighthouses|Dubris]] built by the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] after their conquest of Britain.\n\n* Prof [[Bruce Bilby]], Professor of the Theory of Materials at the [[University of Sheffield]] from 1966\u201384\n* [[Antony Hook]], barrister and [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n* [[Arthur Cockfield, Baron Cockfield]], President of the [[Royal Statistical Society]] from 1968-9, and [[Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills|Secretary of State for Trade]] from 1982-3, European Commission 1984-88\n* [[Eddie Crush]], cricketer\n* [[Harold Gray]] CMG, Director of the National Association of British Manufacturers from 1961-5\n* Sir [[James Menter]], President of the [[Institute of Physics]] from 1970-2, and Principal of [[Queen Mary, University of London|Queen Mary College, London]] from 1976\u201386\n* Rt Rev [[Eric Arthur John Mercer|Eric Mercer]], [[Bishop of Birkenhead]] from 1965\u201373 and [[Bishop of Exeter]] from 1973\u201385\n* Sir [[John Mummery]], aka Lord Justice Mummery, a judge in the Court of Appeal\n* Rt Rev [[Kenneth Albert Newing|Kenneth Newing]], [[Bishop of Plymouth (Anglican)|Bishop of Plymouth]] from 1982-9\n* [[Jonathan Parry]], historian\n* Prof [[David Thomas (geographer)|David Thomas]], Professor of Geography at the [[University of Oxford]] since 2004\n* [[R. J. Unstead]], historical author\n* [[David Thomas (geographer)|David Thomas]], scientist and geographer\n* [[David Elleray]], Former top flight Football referee\n* [[Matthew Carley]], Current International & English Rugby Union referee\n* [[James Brown (footballer, born 1998)|James Brown]], professional footballer for [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]\n*[[R J Unstead]], a prolific author of history books for children, attended the school from 1926 to 1934.\n* [[Topper Headon]], drummer with [[The Clash]].\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://dovergramboys.kent.sch.uk School website]\n* [https://oldpharosians.org.uk/school-history/ School history]\n\n{{Schools in Kent}}\n\n[[Category:Grammar schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dover, Kent|Grammar]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1904]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in England]]\n[[Category:Foundation schools in Kent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2012}}\n{{primary sources|date=February 2012}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British Eng